,Not Recommended,628420,35265660,Posted: 28 September,all,OctoberFox,"401 Deaths LaterI got a coupon and used it to buy a game I probably would have otherwise overlooked. So what did I get for a dime and time played?This was one of the most basic looking games I've ever played. It has almost no visual style that doesn't just look poor. Bigger problems are the parts that appear to be dangerous but are not, and parts that look safe and are unsafe. An example would be spike floors that appear around the middle of the game are barely approachable without instant death.The game relies very heavily on trial and error in a few stages, but is otherwise pretty fairly designed. You will need to watch the timing and movements of hazards more than the hazards themselves. On some stages the hazards were hidden by visual design flaws. A light color would almost totally obscure small floor spikes, making them very hard to see. I was able to get past it eventually, but not without eye strain.I've been playing this game on mute; sound is not what I'd call great. There seem to be no sound effects at all. Music track are grating and annoying, and they reset every time you die, so it's a bit like hitting the skip button through an album after about 30 second into a song.One very odd design mistake is that the instructions on stage one were incorrectly showing that I needed to press the up key to jump. This was wrong. The SPACE BAR is jump.Pros:StraightforwardTechnically functionalCons:Poor controlsNo controller supportNo sound effectsBad musicControls mislabeledVisually uglyVerdict: 2/10I didn't feel like this was time well spent. I've played worse games, but I've played many better ones for sure.TIP:As of the date of this review, I found that you can super jump in certain spots to bypass obstacles. Just tapping the space bar repeatedly will launch the player quite a bit higher than normal, and since there is no falling damage the player only needs to watch out where they land. An easy way to see what I mean is right at the beginning of the first level. Just tap jump repeatedly to launch the player up. Wish I'd have known about this earlier."
